["# Cruise Lines & Disney Properties Edition\nComplete Prompt Framework — 17 Sections with Vertical Intelligence Briefs", "# University of Florida\nCourse Materials — Coaching Edition\n\n\nSelling INTO the Organization | Selling FOR the Organization\nYou are a vendor selling a B2B solution to this\nenterprise. Examples: enterprise software, AI\nworkforce tools, revenue management systems, CRM,\nanalytics, sustainability tech, foodservice supply,\nentertainment systems. | You are this organization, building a GTM to grow its\nown B2B revenue. Examples: expanding Disney\nInstitute corporate training, cruise line group sales\nprograms, corporate event partnerships, loyalty\nplatform licensing, sponsorship sales.", "# | Entity | HQ | B2B Opportunity Notes\n1 | Carnival Corporation & plc | Miami, FL | World’s largest cruise company; 9\nbrands, massive vendor ecosystem\n2 | Royal Caribbean Group | Miami, FL | Technology leader; Icon-class ships;\nmajor AI/digital investment\n3 | Norwegian Cruise Line Holdings | Miami, FL | 3 brands (NCL, Oceania, Regent);\npremium/luxury positioning\n4 | MSC Cruises USA | Fort Lauderdale, FL | Fastest-growing line; European\nparent, US expansion\n5 | Virgin Voyages | Plantation, FL | Disruptor brand; tech-forward, adult-\nonly positioning\n6 | Disney Cruise Line | Celebration, FL | Premium family brand; expanding\nfleet significantly\n7 | Celebrity Cruises | Miami, FL | Premium segment; design/luxury\ndifferentiation\nB2B Sales GTM Plan — AI Prompt Guide\nPage 2", "# Project Overview\nFor your AI-Enabled Sales GTM Project, you will select one enterprise entity from the curated list below.\nThese organizations were selected because they operate at enterprise scale, have complex buying\ncommittees, maintain large vendor ecosystems, support sophisticated B2B sales motions, and offer\nstrong opportunities for AI-enabled sales strategy.", "# Selling INTO vs. Selling FOR\nYou will design a Sales Go-to-Market strategy using one of two approaches:\nSelling INTO the Organization\nSelling FOR the Organization\nYou are a vendor selling a B2B solution to this\nenterprise. Examples: enterprise software, AI\nworkforce tools, revenue management systems, CRM,\nanalytics, sustainability tech, foodservice supply,\nentertainment systems.\nYou are this organization, building a GTM to grow its\nown B2B revenue. Examples: expanding Disney\nInstitute corporate training, cruise line group sales\nprograms, corporate event partnerships, loyalty\nplatform licensing, sponsorship sales.\nEither approach works with the full 17-section GTM framework. Your Master Prompt should clearly state\nwhich direction you are taking.", "#\nEntity\nHQ\nB2B Opportunity Notes\n1\nCarnival Corporation & plc\nMiami, FL\nWorld’s largest cruise company; 9\nbrands, massive vendor ecosystem\n2\nRoyal Caribbean Group\nMiami, FL\nTechnology leader; Icon-class ships;\nmajor AI/digital investment\n3\nNorwegian Cruise Line Holdings\nMiami, FL\n3 brands (NCL, Oceania, Regent);\npremium/luxury positioning\n4\nMSC Cruises USA\nFort Lauderdale, FL\nFastest-growing line; European\nparent, US expansion\n5\nVirgin Voyages\nPlantation, FL\nDisruptor brand; tech-forward, adult-\nonly positioning\n6\nDisney Cruise Line\nCelebration, FL\nPremium family brand; expanding\nfleet significantly\n7\nCelebrity Cruises\nMiami, FL\nPremium segment; design/luxury\ndifferentiation", "# | Entity | HQ | B2B Opportunity Notes\n8 | Holland America Line | Miami, FL | Heritage brand; premium positioning;\nolder demographic\n9 | Princess Cruises | FL operations | MedallionClass technology; Carnival\nCorp subsidiary\n10 | Seabourn Cruise Line | Miami, FL | Ultra-luxury; small ships; expedition\nfocus", "# | Entity | Location | B2B Opportunity Notes\n11 | Magic Kingdom Park | Orlando, FL | Highest attendance theme park\nglobally; massive ops scale\n12 | EPCOT | Orlando, FL | Technology showcase; World\nShowcase sponsorship opportunities\n13 | Disney’s Hollywood Studios | Orlando, FL | IP-driven experiences; Star Wars, Toy\nStory lands\n14 | Disney’s Animal Kingdom | Orlando, FL | Conservation mission; unique vendor\nneeds (animal care, sustainability)\n15 | Disney’s Typhoon Lagoon | Orlando, FL | Seasonal water park; capacity\nmanagement challenges\n16 | Disney’s Blizzard Beach | Orlando, FL | Seasonal water park; complementary\nto Typhoon Lagoon\n17 | Disney’s Grand Floridian | Lake Buena Vista, FL | Flagship luxury resort; premium guest\nexperience\n18 | Disney’s Pop Century Resort | Lake Buena Vista, FL | Value resort; high volume,\noperational efficiency focus\n19 | Disney Springs | Lake Buena Vista, FL | Retail/dining district; tenant/vendor\nB2B relationships\n20 | Disney Institute | Orlando, FL | B2B training/consulting brand;\nstrongest “selling FOR” candidate\nB2B Sales GTM Plan — AI Prompt Guide\nPage 3", "#\nEntity\nHQ\nB2B Opportunity Notes\n8\nHolland America Line\nMiami, FL\nHeritage brand; premium positioning;\nolder demographic\n9\nPrincess Cruises\nFL operations\nMedallionClass technology; Carnival\nCorp subsidiary\n10\nSeabourn Cruise Line\nMiami, FL\nUltra-luxury; small ships; expedition\nfocus", "# Disney Properties (11–20)\nImportant:  Individual Disney parks and resorts do not have independent procurement authority.\nPurchasing decisions are centralized at the Walt Disney World Resort or Walt Disney Parks, Experiences,\nand Products level. When you select a Disney property, treat it as your  use case context . Your solution is\ndeployed at that property, but your buyer is the Walt Disney World operating division. Disney Institute\n(#20) is the exception and operates with greater B2B autonomy.", "#\nEntity\nLocation\nB2B Opportunity Notes\n11\nMagic Kingdom Park\nOrlando, FL\nHighest attendance theme park\nglobally; massive ops scale\n12\nEPCOT\nOrlando, FL\nTechnology showcase; World\nShowcase sponsorship opportunities\n13\nDisney’s Hollywood Studios\nOrlando, FL\nIP-driven experiences; Star Wars, Toy\nStory lands\n14\nDisney’s Animal Kingdom\nOrlando, FL\nConservation mission; unique vendor\nneeds (animal care, sustainability)\n15\nDisney’s Typhoon Lagoon\nOrlando, FL\nSeasonal water park; capacity\nmanagement challenges\n16\nDisney’s Blizzard Beach\nOrlando, FL\nSeasonal water park; complementary\nto Typhoon Lagoon\n17\nDisney’s Grand Floridian\nLake Buena Vista, FL\nFlagship luxury resort; premium guest\nexperience\n18\nDisney’s Pop Century Resort\nLake Buena Vista, FL\nValue resort; high volume,\noperational efficiency focus\n19\nDisney Springs\nLake Buena Vista, FL\nRetail/dining district; tenant/vendor\nB2B relationships\n20\nDisney Institute\nOrlando, FL\nB2B training/consulting brand;\nstrongest “selling FOR” candidate\n\n\nB2B Sales GTM Plan — AI Prompt Guide\nPage 4", "# Selection Rules\n1.   First-come, first-served. Only one team per entity.\n2.   Once selected, specify: (a) Team member names, (b) Whether you are selling INTO or selling\nFOR the organization.\n3.   If your first choice is taken, select another.\n4.   For Disney properties 11–19: your buyer is Walt Disney World Resort (the operating division).\nYour selected property is the deployment context for your solution.\n\n\nB2B Sales GTM Plan — AI Prompt Guide\nPage 5", "# Vertical Intelligence Briefs\nThese briefs provide industry context to help you apply the GTM framework effectively. Reference this\ninformation when completing each section. It will make your prompts more specific and your outputs\nmore credible.", "# 🛳  Cruise Line Industry Brief\nOrganizational Structure & Decision-Making\nMajor cruise corporations (Carnival Corp, Royal Caribbean Group, Norwegian Holdings) operate as\nholding companies with multiple brands. Purchasing decisions vary by category: fleet-wide technology\ndecisions are made at the corporate level by C-suite and VP-level executives, while individual brand or\nship-level decisions may be made by brand presidents or VP Hotel Operations. Procurement\ndepartments manage vendor qualification, RFP processes, and contract negotiation. Typical enterprise\nsales cycles range from 6–18 months, with pilot programs on 1–2 ships before fleet-wide rollout.\nMajor Procurement Categories & Vendor Ecosystem\n•\nTechnology & Digital: Revenue management systems, CRM, guest experience platforms, ship-to-\nshore connectivity, cybersecurity, AI/ML solutions\n•\nMarine Operations: Fuel and energy systems, navigation technology, environmental compliance,\nsafety systems, predictive maintenance\n•\nHotel Operations: Food & beverage supply, entertainment systems, housekeeping technology,\nPOS systems, crew management platforms\n•\nRevenue & Commercial: Pricing optimization, distribution/OTA partnerships, loyalty platforms,\nonboard retail, shore excursion management\n•\nSustainability: Emissions reduction tech, waste management, water treatment, LNG fueling,\nshore power systems\nTypical Buying Process\n•\nVendor qualification/registration (often required before any sales conversation)\n•\nInternal needs identification and budget approval\n•\nRFI/RFP process (formal for large contracts)\n•\nVendor presentations to cross-functional committee\n•\nPilot/proof-of-concept on limited ships\n•\nNegotiation and contracting (multi-year preferred)\n•\nPhased rollout across fleet\nIndustry Terminology\n•\nBerth: A bed/sleeping position on a ship; used to measure capacity (e.g., “5,000-berth ship”)\n•\nPer diem: Revenue or cost measured per passenger per day\n•\nOnboard revenue: Non-ticket revenue (drinks, spa, casino, excursions, retail)\n\n\nB2B Sales GTM Plan — AI Prompt Guide\nPage 6\n•\nTurnaround day: The day a ship ends one voyage and begins another; operationally intensive\n•\nYield management: Dynamic pricing to optimize revenue per available berth\n•\nNewbuild: A ship under construction; major technology decisions are made 2–3 years before\ndelivery\nCurrent Strategic Priorities (2025–2026)\n•\nAI and digital transformation: Guest personalization, predictive operations, dynamic pricing\n•\nFleet expansion: Major newbuild orders across all lines; Royal Caribbean’s Icon class, Disney’s\nnew ships\n•\nSustainability and decarbonization: IMO regulations, LNG adoption, shore power, carbon targets\n•\nPrivate island/destination development: Exclusive ports as competitive differentiators\n•\nCrew experience and retention: Workforce management, training, onboard connectivity\n\n\nB2B Sales GTM Plan — AI Prompt Guide\nPage 7", "# Disney Properties Industry Brief\nOrganizational Structure & Decision-Making\nWalt Disney World Resort in Florida is a division within Disney Parks, Experiences, and Products (DPEP),\na segment of The Walt Disney Company. Individual parks (Magic Kingdom, EPCOT, etc.) and resorts\n(Grand Floridian, Pop Century, etc.) are operating units within Walt Disney World Resort. They do not\nhave independent procurement authority. Major technology, vendor, and infrastructure decisions are\nmade at the Walt Disney World or DPEP level by VPs and SVPs. The exception is Disney Institute, which\noperates as a separate B2B professional development brand with greater autonomy over its commercial\npartnerships.\nMajor Procurement Categories & Vendor Ecosystem\n•\nTechnology & Digital: Guest experience platforms (MagicBand+, My Disney Experience app),\nCRM, park operations systems, data analytics, AI/ML, cybersecurity\n•\nPark Operations: Ride maintenance and safety, crowd flow management, food & beverage\nsupply, merchandise sourcing, waste management\n•\nResort & Hospitality: Property management systems, housekeeping technology, revenue\nmanagement, guest services platforms\n•\nEntertainment & IP: Show systems, audio-animatronics, AR/VR experiences, themed\nenvironment construction\n•\nWorkforce: Cast member training, scheduling optimization, HR systems, labor management for\n75,000+ FL employees\n•\nSustainability: Energy management, water conservation, zero-waste initiatives, carbon reduction\nTypical Buying Process\n•\nVendor registration through Disney’s supplier portal (required before engagement)\n•\nInternal sponsorship by a Disney business owner/VP\n•\nCross-functional review (IT, Operations, Finance, Legal, Procurement)\n•\nProof of concept/pilot at one property or park\n•\nSecurity and compliance review (data privacy is critical given guest data)\n•\nMulti-year contract negotiation with Procurement\n•\nPhased deployment across Walt Disney World properties\nIndustry Terminology\n•\nCast member: Disney’s term for all employees\n•\nGuest: Disney’s term for customers/visitors (never “customer” internally)\n•\nADR (Average Daily Rate): Key hotel revenue metric\n•\nPer caps (per capita spending): Revenue per guest per visit\n•\nDPEP: Disney Parks, Experiences and Products (the corporate segment)\n•\nMagicBand+: Wearable technology for park access, payment, personalization\n•\nGenie+ / Lightning Lane: Paid queue management and ride reservation system\n\n\nB2B Sales GTM Plan — AI Prompt Guide\nPage 8\nCurrent Strategic Priorities (2025–2026)\n•\nMassive capital investment: $60B planned over 10 years for parks expansion globally\n•\nTechnology-driven guest experience: MagicBand+, AI personalization, dynamic pricing for\ntickets, and Lightning Lane\n•\nRevenue optimization: Per-guest spending growth, Genie+ monetization, F&B and merchandise\nuplift\n•\nOperational efficiency: Labor cost management, automation of back-of-house operations,\nenergy optimization\n•\nNew attractions and IP deployment: Epic Universe competitor response, new lands and rides\n\n\nGTM Section | Selling INTO | Selling FOR\nICP (Section 3) | The cruise line or Disney division is your\nICP. Define which operating units, what\nbudget authority, what tech maturity. | External B2B buyers are your ICP. E.g.,\nFortune 500 L&D departments (Disney\nInstitute), corporate event planners\n(cruise groups), travel management\ncompanies.\nBuying Committee\n(Section 4) | Map the internal stakeholders at the\ncruise line or Disney (VP Ops, CTO,\nProcurement, etc.). | Map the buying committee at the\nexternal customer’s organization (e.g.,\nCHRO, VP L&D, CFO for Disney Institute\ncorporate training).\nValue Model\n(Section 5) | Quantify value to the enterprise (cost\nsavings, revenue lift, operational\nefficiency for the cruise line/Disney). | Quantify value to the B2B customer\n(ROI of corporate training, group event\noutcomes, partnership revenue).\nSales Motion\n(Section 7) | Enterprise, high-touch, named-account.\nLong sales cycle. Likely involves RFP and\npilot. | Could range from enterprise to mid-\nmarket depending on customer base.\nMay involve shorter cycles and more\nvolume.\nDemand Gen\n(Section 10) | ABM-heavy, relationship-driven, trade\nshow focused (Seatrade, IAAPA). | Broader mix: content marketing,\noutbound, events, partnerships. More\nchannels in play.\nPipeline Model (Section\n9) | Low volume, high ACV. Few large deals. | Higher volume, moderate ACV. More\nPipeline math driven by enterprise | deals required. Pipeline math driven by\nvelocity. | conversion efficiency.\nB2B Sales GTM Plan — AI Prompt Guide\nPage 9", "# Framing Guide: Selling INTO vs. Selling FOR\nThis section helps you calibrate how the 17-section GTM framework applies differently depending on\nyour chosen direction.\nGTM Section\nSelling INTO\nSelling FOR\nICP (Section 3)\nThe cruise line or Disney division is your\nICP. Define which operating units, what\nbudget authority, what tech maturity.\nExternal B2B buyers are your ICP. E.g.,\nFortune 500 L&D departments (Disney\nInstitute), corporate event planners\n(cruise groups), travel management\ncompanies.\nBuying Committee\n(Section 4)\nMap the internal stakeholders at the\ncruise line or Disney (VP Ops, CTO,\nProcurement, etc.).\nMap the buying committee at the\nexternal customer’s organization (e.g.,\nCHRO, VP L&D, CFO for Disney Institute\ncorporate training).\nValue Model\n(Section 5)\nQuantify value to the enterprise (cost\nsavings, revenue lift, operational\nefficiency for the cruise line/Disney).\nQuantify value to the B2B customer\n(ROI of corporate training, group event\noutcomes, partnership revenue).\nSales Motion\n(Section 7)\nEnterprise, high-touch, named-account.\nLong sales cycle. Likely involves RFP and\npilot.\nCould range from enterprise to mid-\nmarket depending on customer base.\nMay involve shorter cycles and more\nvolume.\nDemand Gen\n(Section 10)\nABM-heavy, relationship-driven, trade\nshow focused (Seatrade, IAAPA).\nBroader mix: content marketing,\noutbound, events, partnerships. More\nchannels in play.\nPipeline Model (Section\n9)\nLow volume, high ACV. Few large deals.\nPipeline math driven by enterprise\nvelocity.\nHigher volume, moderate ACV. More\ndeals required. Pipeline math driven by\nconversion efficiency.\nRecommendation: “Selling INTO” creates the most complex enterprise sales environment and is\nrecommended for most teams. “Selling FOR” works best for the Disney Institute (#20) and cruise line\ngroup/corporate sales programs.\n\n\nB2B Sales GTM Plan — AI Prompt Guide\nPage 10", "# How to Use This Guide\nThis guide provides a complete, step-by-step prompt framework for building a B2B Sales Go-To-Market\nPlan with generative AI. Each section builds on the previous sections, creating a coherent, internally\nconsistent strategy.", "# Rules of Engagement\nBefore starting any section, start a new AI conversation using the Master Prompt below. This sets the\ncontext, tone, and behavioral rules that carry through the entire plan.\nKey principles to follow throughout:\n•\nSequential building: Each section references prior sections. Complete them in order.\n•\nQuantify everything: Replace vague claims with numbers, ranges, or stated assumptions.\n•\nLabel your data: Mark every estimate as [DATA], [ESTIMATE], or [ASSUMPTION].\n•\nUse your Vertical Intelligence Brief: Reference industry context to make prompts more specific.\n•\nChallenge weak logic: If the AI produces generic outputs, push back and ask for specificity.\n•\nIterate, don’t accept first drafts: The first output is a starting point, not a final answer.\n\n\nB2B Sales GTM Plan — AI Prompt Guide\nPage 11", "# Master Prompt\nCopy and paste the following prompt to start your AI-assisted GTM planning session. Fill in the\nbracketed fields with your information.\nYou are a senior B2B commercial strategy consultant with 20 years of experience advising growth-\nstage and enterprise companies on go-to-market strategy, sales architecture, and revenue\noperations. You have deep expertise in the cruise line and hospitality/entertainment industries.\nYou will help me build a comprehensive B2B Sales Go-To-Market Plan across 17 sections. Each section\nbuilds on the previous ones to create a coherent, internally consistent strategy.\nRules of engagement:\n1. BEFORE generating any section, ask 3–5 clarifying questions specific to that section to ensure\nprecision and relevance.\n2. REFERENCE PRIOR SECTIONS. If I have already completed earlier sections, incorporate those inputs.\nDo not contradict or ignore them.\n3. QUANTIFY wherever possible. Replace vague claims with numbers, ranges, or clearly stated\nassumptions.\n4. FLAG WEAK LOGIC. If my inputs contain contradictions or unsupported assumptions, challenge me\ndirectly.\n5. LABEL every estimate: [DATA] = verified data, [ESTIMATE] = informed projection, [ASSUMPTION] =\nunvalidated belief.\n6. USE STRUCTURED OUTPUT — tables, frameworks, and clearly labeled subsections. Board-ready\nformatting.\n7. MAINTAIN COHERENCE — at the end of each section, note how it connects to the next section and\nflag any emerging inconsistencies.\nMy selected entity: [ENTITY NAME from selection list]\nEntity number: [#1–20]\nGTM Direction: [SELLING INTO / SELLING FOR]\nIf SELLING INTO, describe:\n• What product/solution are you selling? [description]\n• What problem does it solve for this entity? [description]\n• Company stage: [e.g., Series B, bootstrapped, enterprise division]\n• Current ARR: [if applicable]\n\n\nB2B Sales GTM Plan — AI Prompt Guide\nPage 12\nIf SELLING FOR, describe:\n• Which B2B offering are you building a GTM for? [description]\n• Who is the target B2B customer? [description]\n• Current state of this B2B business: [new initiative / existing but growing / mature]\nConfirm you understand these rules, then ask your clarifying questions for Section 1: Executive\nOverview.\n\n\nPhase | Sections | Focus\nStrategy | 1–3 | Executive Overview, Market Analysis, ICP\nArchitecture | 4–9 | Buying Committee, Value Model, Pricing, Sales Motion,\nCustomer Journey, Pipeline Model\nExecution | 10–14 | Demand Gen, Enablement, AI Strategy, KPIs, 90-Day Plan\nDefense | 15–17 | Risk Mitigation, Board Defense, Coherence Check\nB2B Sales GTM Plan — AI Prompt Guide\nPage 13", "# Section Overview\nThe GTM plan is organized into 17 sections across four phases:\nPhase\nSections\nFocus\nStrategy\n1–3\nExecutive Overview, Market Analysis, ICP\nArchitecture\n4–9\nBuying Committee, Value Model, Pricing, Sales Motion,\nCustomer Journey, Pipeline Model\nExecution\n10–14\nDemand Gen, Enablement, AI Strategy, KPIs, 90-Day Plan\nDefense\n15–17\nRisk Mitigation, Board Defense, Coherence Check\n\n\nSection 1: Executive Overview\nPage 14\nSECTION 1", "# Educational Purpose\nForces strategic clarity. Students must articulate the core growth thesis, define success in numerical\nterms, and identify assumptions before diving into tactics. This prevents fragmented, disconnected\nstrategic work.", "# AI Prompt\nCopy and paste the following prompt into your AI conversation after completing the prior section:\nUsing the company context I provided in the Master Prompt, develop a concise Executive Overview\nfor this GTM plan. Include:\n(1) GTM Thesis: A 3–5 sentence strategic narrative explaining what we sell, to whom, why now, and\nhow we win.\n(2) 12–24 Month Revenue Target: Specify the target with underlying assumptions (e.g., ACV, number\nof deals, growth rate).\n(3) Competitive Positioning: One paragraph on how we are differentiated and defensible.\n(4) 3–5 Critical Assumptions: What must be true for this GTM to succeed? Label each as [VALIDATED],\n[PARTIALLY VALIDATED], or [UNVALIDATED].\n(5) Strategic Priorities: The 3 things that matter most in the next 12 months.\nImportant: If I am selling INTO my selected entity, frame the thesis around the vendor’s value\nproposition to that enterprise buyer. If I am selling FOR the entity, frame the thesis around the\nentity’s own B2B revenue growth. Reference the Vertical Intelligence Brief for industry context.\nUse a board-ready tone. Be specific, not generic. If any of my inputs are vague, challenge me before\nproceeding.\n\n\nSection 1: Executive Overview\nPage 15", "# Expected Deliverables\n•\nGTM thesis statement\n•\nRevenue target with assumptions\n•\nCompetitive positioning paragraph\n•\nCritical assumptions with validation status\n•\nTop 3 strategic priorities\nCoherence Check\nBefore moving to Section 2, review this section’s outputs against prior sections. Ask the AI: “Does this\nsection contradict or weaken anything in Sections 1–1? If so, what should I adjust?”\n\n\nSection 2: Market & Opportunity Analysis\nPage 16\nSECTION 2", "# Educational Purpose\nTeaches structured market sizing and competitive awareness. Students must quantify TAM/SAM/SOM\nwith defensible logic and assess structural forces, not merely describe trends.", "# AI Prompt\nCopy and paste the following prompt into your AI conversation after completing the prior section:\nReferencing the Executive Overview from Section 1, conduct a Market & Opportunity Analysis.\nInclude:\n(1) TAM/SAM/SOM Estimates: Use a bottom-up and top-down approach. Show your math step-by-\nstep. Label data as [DATA], [ESTIMATE], or [ASSUMPTION].\n• For “selling INTO”: TAM = total addressable spend by cruise lines / Disney properties in your\nproduct category. SAM = the subset you can realistically reach. SOM = year-one target.\n• For “selling FOR”: TAM = the total B2B market for the entity’s offering. SAM/SOM = addressable\nand capturable segments.\n(2) Market Growth Rate: Annual growth rate with source or reasoning.\n(3) Porter’s Five Forces Assessment: Score each force (Low / Medium / High) with a 1–2 sentence\njustification.\n(4) Competitive Landscape: Identify 4–6 competitors. For each: positioning, strengths, weaknesses,\nestimated market share.\n(5) Buying Behavior Shifts: 2–3 trends changing how buyers in this market evaluate and purchase\nsolutions.\n(6) Opportunity Summary: What structural market conditions make this a compelling GTM\nopportunity right now?\nPresent TAM/SAM/SOM in a table. Use structured outputs throughout.\n\n\nSection 2: Market & Opportunity Analysis\nPage 17", "# Expected Deliverables\n•\nTAM/SAM/SOM table with math\n•\nPorter's Five Forces summary\n•\nCompetitive landscape matrix\n•\nBuying behavior trends\n•\nOpportunity summary\nCoherence Check\nBefore moving to Section 3, review this section’s outputs against prior sections. Ask the AI: “Does this\nsection contradict or weaken anything in Sections 1–1? If so, what should I adjust?”\n\n\nSection 3: Ideal Customer Profile (ICP)\nPage 18\nSECTION 3", "# Educational Purpose\nForces prioritization. Students must define who they will NOT sell to. Focuses on profitability and sales\nefficiency over broad, unfocused segmentation.", "# AI Prompt\nCopy and paste the following prompt into your AI conversation after completing the prior section:\nUsing the Market Analysis from Section 2, define the Ideal Customer Profile. Include:\n(1) Primary ICP: Firmographics (industry, company size, revenue range, geography), technographics\n(current stack, adoption maturity), and organizational characteristics (growth stage, team structure).\n• For “selling INTO”: Your ICP is the enterprise buyer (e.g., cruise lines with 5+ ships, Disney\nproperties with specific operational needs). Define which divisions, business units, or operating\nentities are your best-fit buyers.\n• For “selling FOR”: Your ICP is the external B2B customer the entity wants to reach (e.g., corporate\nevent planners, travel management companies, Fortune 500 L&D departments for Disney Institute).\n(2) Trigger Events: 3–5 specific events that signal a prospect is ready to buy (e.g., fleet expansion,\nnew property opening, technology refresh cycle, leadership change).\n(3) Pain Intensity Ranking: Rank the top 3–5 pains by severity and urgency. Explain why each pain\njustifies action now.\n(4) Anti-ICP: Define 3–5 characteristics of organizations you should NOT pursue and why.\n(5) ICP Prioritization Logic: Explain why this ICP maximizes LTV, win rate, and sales efficiency.\n(6) Secondary ICP (if applicable): A second segment to expand into after establishing the primary\nbeachhead.\nFormat the ICP as a reference card a sales rep could use in 30 seconds.\n\n\nSection 3: Ideal Customer Profile (ICP)\nPage 19", "# Expected Deliverables\n•\nPrimary ICP reference card\n•\nTrigger events list\n•\nPain intensity ranking\n•\nAnti-ICP definition\n•\nPrioritization logic\n•\nSecondary ICP (optional)\nCoherence Check\nBefore moving to Section 4, review this section’s outputs against prior sections. Ask the AI: “Does this\nsection contradict or weaken anything in Sections 1–2? If so, what should I adjust?”\n\n\nSection 4: Buying Committee Architecture\nPage 20\nSECTION 4", "# Educational Purpose\nIntroduces real B2B complexity. Students must understand multi-stakeholder selling dynamics, internal\npolitical friction, and champion enablement within large enterprise organizations.", "# AI Prompt\nCopy and paste the following prompt into your AI conversation after completing the prior section:\nUsing the ICP from Section 3, map the full buying committee for a typical deal. For each stakeholder\nrole, provide:\n| Role | Typical Titles | Core Concern | Likely Objection | Messaging Angle | Influence Level (1–5) |\nWhen They Enter the Deal |\nRoles to map: Economic Buyer, Technical Buyer/Evaluator, End User, Champion/Internal Advocate,\nProcurement/Legal, Executive Sponsor (if different from Economic Buyer).\nIndustry-specific guidance:\n• Cruise lines: Buying committees often span corporate HQ (Miami) and shipboard operations.\nInclude VP Marine Operations, VP Hotel Operations, VP Revenue Management, Chief Digital/IT\nOfficer, and Procurement as likely stakeholders. Note that fleet-wide rollouts require both shore-side\nand shipboard buy-in.\n• Disney properties: Purchasing decisions are centralized at the Walt Disney World Resort or Walt\nDisney Parks, Experiences and Products level. Individual parks and resorts do not have independent\nprocurement authority. Map the committee at the operating division level.\nThen address:\n(a) Deal-Stalling Personas: Which role most commonly stalls or kills deals, and why?\n(b) Political Dynamics: What internal tensions exist between stakeholders that could create friction?\n(c) Champion Enablement: What materials, data, or talking points does your champion need to sell\ninternally on your behalf?\n(d) Consensus Building: How many stakeholders typically need to say yes? What is the approval\nchain?\n\n\nSection 4: Buying Committee Architecture\nPage 21", "# Expected Deliverables\n•\nBuying committee map (table)\n•\nDeal-stalling analysis\n•\nPolitical dynamics assessment\n•\nChampion enablement toolkit\n•\nConsensus/approval chain\nCoherence Check\nBefore moving to Section 5, review this section’s outputs against prior sections. Ask the AI: “Does this\nsection contradict or weaken anything in Sections 1–3? If so, what should I adjust?”\n\n\nSection 5: Value Quantification Model\nPage 22\nSECTION 5", "# Educational Purpose\nMoves students from qualitative benefits to financial proof. Teaches ROI modeling and translation of\nproduct value into economic terms buyers can approve internally.", "# AI Prompt\nCopy and paste the following prompt into your AI conversation after completing the prior section:\nUsing the ICP (Section 3) and Buying Committee (Section 4), build a Value Quantification Model.\nInclude:\n(1) Value Drivers: Identify 3–5 quantifiable value drivers. For each:\n• Category: Cost Savings / Revenue Lift / Risk Reduction / Time Savings / Productivity Gain\n• Calculation: Show the formula and inputs\n• Conservative / Moderate / Aggressive estimates\n• Data source or assumption label\nIndustry context:\n• Cruise lines: Think in terms of per-berth revenue, onboard spend per passenger, fuel cost per\nnautical mile, crew labor cost per ship, turnaround time at port, and guest satisfaction scores (NPS).\nThese are the financial levers that matter.\n• Disney properties: Think in terms of per-guest spending, park capacity utilization, average daily\nhotel rate (ADR), labor cost per cast member, guest experience scores, and annual passholder\nretention.\n(2) ROI Model: Calculate total annual value, solution cost, net ROI %, and payback period in months.\n(3) Stakeholder-Specific Value: Map which value drivers matter most to each buying committee\nmember.\n(4) Proof Points: What evidence validates each value driver? Label as [AVAILABLE], [NEEDED], or [IN\nPROGRESS].\n(5) Value Narrative: A 3–4 sentence executive summary of the financial case.\nAll claims must be quantified. No qualitative-only statements. Label every number as [DATA],\n[ESTIMATE], or [ASSUMPTION].\n\n\nSection 5: Value Quantification Model\nPage 23", "# Expected Deliverables\n•\nValue driver table with calculations\n•\nROI model with payback period\n•\nStakeholder-value mapping\n•\nProof point inventory\n•\nExecutive value narrative\nCoherence Check\nBefore moving to Section 6, review this section’s outputs against prior sections. Ask the AI: “Does this\nsection contradict or weaken anything in Sections 1–4? If so, what should I adjust?”\n\n\nSection 6: Pricing & Packaging Strategy\nPage 24\nSECTION 6", "# Educational Purpose\nPricing is where strategy meets revenue. Students must design pricing that aligns with value delivered,\nsupports the sales motion, and creates expansion opportunities.", "# AI Prompt\nCopy and paste the following prompt into your AI conversation after completing the prior section:\nUsing the Value Quantification Model (Section 5) and ICP (Section 3), design a Pricing & Packaging\nStrategy. Include:\n(1) Pricing Model: Recommend a model (per-seat, usage-based, tiered, flat-rate, hybrid) and justify\nbased on how the customer derives value.\n• For “selling INTO” cruise/Disney: Enterprise deals in these industries often involve multi-year\ncontracts, RFP processes, and pilot-to-scale rollouts. Design pricing that supports a land-and-expand\nmotion (e.g., pilot on 2 ships, then fleet-wide; pilot at one park, then resort-wide).\n• For “selling FOR”: Design pricing for the entity’s B2B customers (e.g., corporate group rates,\nlicensing fees, sponsorship tiers).\n(2) Packaging Tiers: Define 2–4 tiers with name, target segment, included features, price point or\nrange, and strategic purpose.\n(3) Pricing Anchoring: How does your pricing relate to the value quantified in Section 5? What is the\nvalue-to-price ratio?\n(4) Discounting Policy: Define guardrails (maximum discount %, who can approve, when discounting\nis acceptable).\n(5) Expansion Levers: How do you grow revenue within existing accounts? (e.g., additional\nships/properties, new use cases, increased usage)\n(6) Competitive Price Positioning: Where do you sit vs. competitors? Premium, parity, or undercut?\nWhy?\nIf pricing data is sensitive or unavailable, provide a framework with placeholder ranges and label\nassumptions.\n\n\nSection 6: Pricing & Packaging Strategy\nPage 25", "# Expected Deliverables\n•\nPricing model recommendation\n•\nPackaging tier table\n•\nValue-to-price ratio analysis\n•\nDiscounting guardrails\n•\nExpansion lever strategy\n•\nCompetitive pricing position\nCoherence Check\nBefore moving to Section 7, review this section’s outputs against prior sections. Ask the AI: “Does this\nsection contradict or weaken anything in Sections 1–5? If so, what should I adjust?”\n\n\nSection 7: Sales Motion Design\nPage 26\nSECTION 7", "# Educational Purpose\nTeaches commercial architecture decisions. Students must choose a scalable sales structure aligned with\ndeal size, complexity, and buyer behavior.", "# AI Prompt\nCopy and paste the following prompt into your AI conversation after completing the prior section:\nUsing Sections 3–6, design the Sales Motion. Include:\n(1) Sales Motion Type: Given the enterprise scale of cruise lines and Disney, this will likely be a high-\ntouch enterprise motion. Justify based on ACV, sales cycle length, and buyer complexity.\n(2) Coverage Model: How are reps organized? For selling INTO these entities, consider named-\naccount or vertical-specialist models. For selling FOR, consider segment-based or geographic\ncoverage.\n(3) Direct vs. Channel Strategy: What percentage of revenue comes from direct sales vs.\npartners/resellers/system integrators? In hospitality/entertainment, channel partners (consulting\nfirms, system integrators, travel trade) often play a significant role.\n(4) Sales Process Stages: Define 5–7 stages with entry criteria, exit criteria, key activities, and stage\nconversion rates.\n(5) Deal Qualification Framework: BANT, MEDDIC, or MEDDPICC. Define the criteria and how reps\napply it. For enterprise hospitality deals, MEDDPICC is recommended given the complexity.\n(6) Team Structure: Roles needed (SDR, AE, SE, AM, CSM). Define ratios and responsibilities.\n(7) Scaling Risks: What breaks first as you scale this motion? What are the early warning signs?\nReference the buying committee and ICP to justify structural decisions.\n\n\nSection 7: Sales Motion Design\nPage 27", "# Expected Deliverables\n•\nSales motion type with justification\n•\nCoverage model\n•\nDirect vs. channel split\n•\nSales process stage map\n•\nQualification framework\n•\nTeam structure and ratios\n•\nScaling risk assessment\nCoherence Check\nBefore moving to Section 8, review this section’s outputs against prior sections. Ask the AI: “Does this\nsection contradict or weaken anything in Sections 1–6? If so, what should I adjust?”\n\n\nSection 8: Customer Journey & Sales Process Mapping\nPage 28\nSECTION 8", "# Educational Purpose\nConnects the buyer’s experience to internal sales execution. Students must map how buyers move\nthrough awareness to decision and align every internal action to that journey.", "# AI Prompt\nCopy and paste the following prompt into your AI conversation after completing the prior section:\nUsing the Sales Motion (Section 7) and Buying Committee (Section 4), map the Customer Journey\nalongside the internal Sales Process. Include:\n(1) Buyer Journey Stages: Awareness → Consideration → Evaluation → Decision → Onboarding. For\neach stage:\n• Buyer’s key question at this stage\n• Information they seek\n• Who on the buying committee is active\n• Emotional state and risk perception\nIndustry note: Enterprise buying cycles in cruise and hospitality often include formal RFP/RFI stages,\nvendor presentations to committee, pilot/proof-of-concept phases, and procurement negotiation.\nMap these explicitly.\n(2) Sales Process Alignment: For each buyer stage, define corresponding internal sales stage, key\nsales activities, required content/assets, and stage entry/exit criteria.\n(3) Friction Points: Where do deals stall or die? What causes it? What is the mitigation?\n(4) Handoff Points: Where does the prospect move between teams? Define handoff criteria and SLAs.\n(5) Time-in-Stage Benchmarks: How long should a deal spend in each stage? What triggers\nescalation?\nPresent as a side-by-side journey map (buyer view | seller view).\n\n\nSection 8: Customer Journey & Sales Process Mapping\nPage 29", "# Expected Deliverables\n•\nBuyer journey map\n•\nSales process alignment table\n•\nFriction point analysis\n•\nHandoff protocols with SLAs\n•\nTime-in-stage benchmarks\nCoherence Check\nBefore moving to Section 9, review this section’s outputs against prior sections. Ask the AI: “Does this\nsection contradict or weaken anything in Sections 1–7? If so, what should I adjust?”\n\n\nSection 9: Revenue & Pipeline Model\nPage 30\nSECTION 9", "# Educational Purpose\nIntroduces pipeline math and revenue mechanics. Students must reverse-engineer activity requirements\nfrom revenue targets and understand the math that drives commercial execution.", "# AI Prompt\nCopy and paste the following prompt into your AI conversation after completing the prior section:\nUsing the Revenue Target (Section 1), Sales Motion (Section 7), and Sales Process (Section 8), build a\nRevenue & Pipeline Model. Show all math step-by-step.\n(1) Revenue Inputs: Annual revenue target, Average ACV (by segment if applicable), Number of new\ndeals required = Revenue Target ÷ ACV.\n(2) Pipeline Math: Win rate (overall and by stage), average sales cycle length, pipeline coverage ratio\n(typically 3–5x), total pipeline needed, opportunities required per quarter.\n(3) Activity Model: Meetings to generate one qualified opportunity, outbound touches per meeting,\nmonthly activity targets per SDR and per AE.\n(4) Capacity Planning: Quota per rep, ramp time for new reps, number of ramped reps required, total\nheadcount plan.\n(5) Sensitivity Analysis: What happens to the model if win rate drops 5%? If ACV decreases 15%? If\nsales cycle extends 30%?\nNote: For enterprise deals with cruise lines and Disney, sales cycles are typically 6–18 months with\nhigh ACV. Pipeline math should reflect longer cycles and lower volume with higher deal values.\nStudents should model realistic enterprise velocity, not SaaS velocity.\nLabel every input as [DATA], [ESTIMATE], or [ASSUMPTION]. Present as a calculable model, not a\nnarrative.\n\n\nSection 9: Revenue & Pipeline Model\nPage 31", "# Expected Deliverables\n•\nRevenue waterfall model\n•\nPipeline math table\n•\nActivity model per role\n•\nCapacity/headcount plan\n•\nSensitivity analysis (3 scenarios)\nCoherence Check\nBefore moving to Section 10, review this section’s outputs against prior sections. Ask the AI: “Does this\nsection contradict or weaken anything in Sections 1–8? If so, what should I adjust?”\n\n\nSection 10: Demand Generation & Acquisition\nPage 32\nSECTION 10", "# Educational Purpose\nTeaches marketing-sales alignment. Students must connect ICP behavior to acquisition channels,\nquantify pipeline contribution per channel, and build a balanced demand engine.", "# AI Prompt\nCopy and paste the following prompt into your AI conversation after completing the prior section:\nUsing the ICP (Section 3), Pipeline Model (Section 9), and Customer Journey (Section 8), design a\nDemand Generation & Acquisition plan. Include:\n(1) Channel Strategy: For each channel (Inbound Content, Outbound SDR, ABM,\nPartnerships/Channel, Events/Conferences, Digital/Paid, Product-Led/Trials):\n• Strategy description, estimated % contribution to pipeline, cost per opportunity estimate, time to\nimpact, ICP alignment rationale.\nIndustry-specific channels to consider:\n• Cruise industry: Seatrade Cruise Global (major trade show), CLIA events, maritime technology\nconferences, cruise line innovation summits, and executive relationship-driven selling.\n• Disney/theme parks: IAAPA Expo, themed entertainment conferences, Disney vendor qualification\nprograms, and industry associations like TEA (Themed Entertainment Association).\n(2) Inbound Engine: Content strategy, SEO/SEM approach, lead magnets, and nurture sequences.\n(3) Outbound Engine: Prospecting strategy, cadence design, personalization approach.\n(4) ABM Strategy: For named enterprise accounts, define tiered approach (1:1, 1:few, 1:many) and\norchestration.\n(5) Channel Mix Allocation: Budget allocation by channel with expected pipeline output.\n(6) Marketing-Sales SLA: Define MQL → SQL handoff criteria, response time SLAs, and feedback loops.\nTie every channel to ICP behavior—where do these buyers spend time, and how do they prefer to\nlearn?\n\n\nSection 10: Demand Generation & Acquisition\nPage 33", "# Expected Deliverables\n•\nChannel strategy matrix\n•\nInbound engine plan\n•\nOutbound playbook\n•\nABM strategy\n•\nBudget allocation table\n•\nMarketing-Sales SLA\nCoherence Check\nBefore moving to Section 11, review this section’s outputs against prior sections. Ask the AI: “Does this\nsection contradict or weaken anything in Sections 1–9? If so, what should I adjust?”\n\n\nSection 11: Sales Enablement\nPage 34\nSECTION 11", "# Educational Purpose\nTeaches win-rate improvement levers. Students must design assets that reduce friction in the sales\nprocess and accelerate deal velocity.", "# AI Prompt\nCopy and paste the following prompt into your AI conversation after completing the prior section:\nUsing the Sales Process (Section 8), Value Model (Section 5), and Buying Committee (Section 4),\ndesign a Sales Enablement program. Include:\n(1) Pitch Deck Structure: Outline slide-by-slide with the narrative arc (situation → complication →\nresolution → proof → ask).\n(2) ROI Calculator: Define inputs, outputs, and logic so a rep can customize in real-time during a sales\ncall. Use industry-specific metrics (per-berth revenue for cruise, per-guest spend for Disney).\n(3) Case Study Framework: Template including customer profile, challenge, solution, quantified\nresults, and quote.\n(4) Objection Handling Guide: Top 10 objections mapped to buying committee role, root cause,\nresponse framework, and proof points.\n(5) Demo Narrative: Structure for a compelling product demo aligned to the buyer journey.\n(6) Competitive Battlecards: For top 3 competitors—positioning, strengths, weaknesses, landmines to\nset, and traps to avoid.\n(7) Email/Outreach Templates: 3–5 templates for different stages and personas.\n(8) Enablement Calendar: A 90-day training and rollout plan for the sales team.\nFocus on assets that directly increase win rate and reduce sales cycle length. Justify each asset’s\ninclusion.\n\n\nSection 11: Sales Enablement\nPage 35", "# Expected Deliverables\n•\nPitch deck outline\n•\nROI calculator logic\n•\nCase study template\n•\nObjection handling guide (top 10)\n•\nDemo narrative structure\n•\nCompetitive battlecards (top 3)\n•\nOutreach templates\n•\n90-day enablement calendar\nCoherence Check\nBefore moving to Section 12, review this section’s outputs against prior sections. Ask the AI: “Does this\nsection contradict or weaken anything in Sections 1–10? If so, what should I adjust?”\n\n\nSection 12: AI-Enabled Sales Strategy\nPage 36\nSECTION 12", "# Educational Purpose\nBuilds AI fluency in commercial application. Students must move beyond generic AI hype to specific,\noperational use cases with measurable revenue impact.", "# AI Prompt\nCopy and paste the following prompt into your AI conversation after completing the prior section:\nDesign an AI-Enabled Sales Strategy that integrates into the GTM plan. For each use case:\n| Use Case | AI Application | Tool/Platform | Sales Stage Impacted | Estimated Impact |\nImplementation Complexity | Risk |\nCover these domains:\n(1) Prospecting & Lead Scoring: AI-powered ICP matching, intent signals, predictive scoring.\n(2) Personalization at Scale: Dynamic email generation, account research automation, custom pitch\ncreation.\n(3) Sales Forecasting: Pipeline prediction, deal risk scoring, revenue forecasting accuracy.\n(4) CRM Automation: Data entry, activity logging, next-best-action recommendations.\n(5) Deal Coaching: Call analysis, objection pattern recognition, win/loss insights.\n(6) Competitive Intelligence: Real-time competitor monitoring, pricing alerts, market signal tracking.\nIndustry-specific AI opportunities:\n• Cruise lines: Dynamic pricing optimization, predictive maintenance vendor sales, AI-powered guest\npersonalization, crew scheduling optimization, itinerary revenue modeling.\n• Disney properties: Guest experience prediction, dynamic capacity management, personalized upsell\nengines, cast member workforce optimization, and MagicBand/app data analytics.\nEstimate efficiency gains or win-rate impact per domain. Identify risks including data quality,\nadoption barriers, and ethical considerations.\nClose with an AI implementation roadmap: Phase 1 (quick wins, 0–3 months), Phase 2 (integration,\n3–6 months), Phase 3 (transformation, 6–12 months).\n\n\nSection 12: AI-Enabled Sales Strategy\nPage 37", "# Expected Deliverables\n•\nAI use case matrix (table)\n•\nImpact estimates per domain\n•\nRisk assessment\n•\n3-phase implementation roadmap\nCoherence Check\nBefore moving to Section 13, review this section’s outputs against prior sections. Ask the AI: “Does this\nsection contradict or weaken anything in Sections 1–11? If so, what should I adjust?”\n\n\nSection 13: KPIs & Dashboard Design\nPage 38\nSECTION 13", "# Educational Purpose\nTeaches measurement discipline. Students must differentiate leading vs. lagging indicators, define\ntargets, and align metrics directly with strategic execution.", "# AI Prompt\nCopy and paste the following prompt into your AI conversation after completing the prior section:\nUsing the Revenue Model (Section 9) and Sales Process (Section 8), define the KPI framework and\ndashboard design. Include:\n(1) Leading Indicators: Metrics that predict future performance (e.g., qualified pipeline created,\nmeetings booked, proposals sent). For each: definition, target, measurement frequency, owner.\n(2) Lagging Indicators: Metrics that confirm results (e.g., revenue closed, deals won). Same structure.\n(3) Efficiency Metrics: CAC, LTV, LTV:CAC ratio, sales velocity, magic number, rep productivity,\npipeline conversion rates.\n(4) Health Metrics: Pipeline aging, stage conversion rates, forecast accuracy, rep attainment\ndistribution.\n(5) Dashboard Layout: Describe an executive dashboard (what a VP of Sales or CRO would review\nweekly).\n(6) Metric Alignment: Show how each KPI connects to a specific strategic assumption or GTM lever.\nFor each metric, specify: definition, formula, target, red/yellow/green thresholds, frequency, and\nstrategic importance.\n\n\nSection 13: KPIs & Dashboard Design\nPage 39", "# Expected Deliverables\n•\nLeading indicator table\n•\nLagging indicator table\n•\nEfficiency metrics with formulas\n•\nHealth metrics\n•\nExecutive dashboard wireframe\n•\nMetric-to-strategy alignment map\nCoherence Check\nBefore moving to Section 14, review this section’s outputs against prior sections. Ask the AI: “Does this\nsection contradict or weaken anything in Sections 1–12? If so, what should I adjust?”\n\n\nSection 14: 90-Day Launch Plan\nPage 40\nSECTION 14", "# Educational Purpose\nForces operationalization. Students must translate strategy into a phased execution roadmap with clear\nmilestones, owners, and accountability.", "# AI Prompt\nCopy and paste the following prompt into your AI conversation after completing the prior section:\nBuild a 90-Day Launch Plan that operationalizes the GTM strategy. Structure in three phases:\nPhase 1 — Foundation (Days 1–30): Infrastructure setup, team onboarding, initial enablement, first\noutbound campaigns. Milestones and success criteria.\nPhase 2 — Activation (Days 31–60): Full campaign execution, first conversion data, process\nrefinements, first qualified opportunities. Milestones and success criteria.\nPhase 3 — Acceleration (Days 61–90): Scale what works, first closed deals or advanced pipeline,\nwin/loss analysis, forecast calibration. Milestones and success criteria.\nFor enterprise sales into cruise/Disney entities, note that 90 days may only get you through early\npipeline generation given 6–18 month sales cycles. Frame Phase 3 milestones around pipeline quality\nand advancement rather than closed revenue.\nFor each phase, define specific deliverables, owners, dependencies, and success criteria. Include a risk\nflag for each phase.", "# Expected Deliverables\n•\n30-day milestone plan\n•\n60-day milestone plan\n•\n90-day milestone plan\n•\nDependency map\n•\nPhase-level risk flags with contingencies\n\n\nSection 14: 90-Day Launch Plan\nPage 41\nCoherence Check\nBefore moving to Section 15, review this section’s outputs against prior sections. Ask the AI: “Does this\nsection contradict or weaken anything in Sections 1–13? If so, what should I adjust?”\n\n\nSection 15: Risk & Mitigation\nPage 42\nSECTION 15", "# Educational Purpose\nIntroduces executive skepticism. Students must stress-test their own assumptions, anticipate failure\npoints, and demonstrate strategic maturity.", "# AI Prompt\nCopy and paste the following prompt into your AI conversation after completing the prior section:\nAct as a skeptical CFO reviewing this GTM plan. Identify and assess risks across four categories:\n(1) Market Risks (3 risks): e.g., industry downturn, regulatory change (maritime/safety regulations),\nbuyer budget freezes, geopolitical disruption to cruise operations.\n(2) Execution Risks (3 risks): e.g., hiring delays, enterprise sales cycle longer than modeled, vendor\nqualification barriers at Disney/cruise lines.\n(3) Financial Risks (3 risks): e.g., CAC exceeds target, ACV compression, slower ramp than projected.\n(4) Competitive Risks (3 risks): e.g., incumbent vendor lock-in, cruise line/Disney building in-house,\nnew entrant disruption.\nFor each risk:\n| Risk | Category | Severity (1–5) | Probability (1–5) | Risk Score | Early Warning Signal | Mitigation\nPlan | Owner |\nIdentify the top 3 existential risks. Cross-reference against critical assumptions from Section 1.", "# Expected Deliverables\n•\nRisk matrix (12 risks, 4 categories)\n•\nRisk scoring table\n•\nTop 3 existential risks\n•\nEarly warning indicators\n•\nAssumption-to-risk cross-reference\n\n\nSection 15: Risk & Mitigation\nPage 43\nCoherence Check\nBefore moving to Section 16, review this section’s outputs against prior sections. Ask the AI: “Does this\nsection contradict or weaken anything in Sections 1–14? If so, what should I adjust?”\n\n\nSection 16: Board Defense Preparation\nPage 44\nSECTION 16", "# Educational Purpose\nForces synthesis and narrative clarity. Students must defend the coherence and strategic logic of the\nentire plan as if presenting to investors or a board.", "# AI Prompt\nCopy and paste the following prompt into your AI conversation after completing the prior section:\nPrepare Board Defense responses for the following questions. Each answer should be 3–5 sentences,\ninvestor-ready, and reference specific data from prior sections.\n(1) Why will this GTM succeed?\n(2) Why now? What is the market timing advantage?\n(3) What are the 3 assumptions most likely to be wrong, and what is the fallback?\n(4) What is the single biggest vulnerability in this plan?\n(5) What must be true in 12 months for us to say this GTM worked?\n(6) How does the unit economics model hold up under stress?\n(7) Why this sales motion over alternatives?\n(8) What is the competitive moat, and how durable is it?\n(9) Where will the first revenue come from, and how confident are you?\n(10) If you had to cut the budget by 30%, what would you cut and what would you protect?\nFor each, anticipate the follow-up question a skeptical board member would ask, and prepare that\nresponse too.", "# Expected Deliverables\n•\n10 board-ready responses\n•\n10 anticipated follow-up Q&As\n•\nSynthesized strategic narrative\n\n\nSection 16: Board Defense Preparation\nPage 45\nCoherence Check\nBefore moving to Section 17, review this section’s outputs against prior sections. Ask the AI: “Does this\nsection contradict or weaken anything in Sections 1–15? If so, what should I adjust?”\n\n\nSection 17: Strategic Coherence Check\nPage 46\nSECTION 17", "# Educational Purpose\nTeaches systems thinking. Students must test internal alignment across every element of the GTM and\nidentify inconsistencies before an evaluator does.", "# AI Prompt\nCopy and paste the following prompt into your AI conversation after completing the prior section:\nReview the entire GTM plan (Sections 1–16) as a unified strategy. Evaluate coherence across these\ndimensions:\n(1) ICP ↔ Sales Motion: Is the sales motion appropriately designed for the ICP’s buying behavior and\ndeal complexity?\n(2) Value Model ↔ Pricing: Does pricing reflect a defensible value-to-price ratio?\n(3) Revenue Target ↔ Pipeline Math: Do the activity levels, rep capacity, and conversion rates\nrealistically support the revenue target?\n(4) Demand Gen ↔ ICP Behavior: Are the acquisition channels aligned with where and how the ICP\nactually buys?\n(5) AI Strategy ↔ Sales Process: Are AI use cases integrated into the sales workflow, or are they\nbolted on?\n(6) KPIs ↔ Strategy: Does every key metric map to a strategic lever or assumption?\n(7) Risks ↔ Assumptions: Is every unvalidated assumption covered by a risk and mitigation plan?\n(8) 90-Day Plan ↔ Revenue Model: Are the launch milestones realistic given the pipeline math and\nenterprise sales cycle?\nFor each dimension, rate alignment as Strong / Moderate / Weak and provide specific evidence.\nIdentify the top 3 inconsistencies and recommend corrective actions.\nClose with a 1-paragraph overall strategic coherence assessment.\n\n\nSection 17: Strategic Coherence Check\nPage 47", "# Expected Deliverables\n•\n8-dimension coherence matrix\n•\nAlignment ratings with evidence\n•\nTop 3 inconsistencies\n•\nCorrective actions\n•\nOverall coherence assessment\nCoherence Check\nThis is the final section. The AI should review the entire plan for internal consistency and provide a\nholistic coherence assessment.\n\n\nAppendix\nPage 48", "# Appendix A: AI Prompting Best Practices\n1. Be Specific, Not Generic\nInstead of “We sell software to businesses,” say “We sell an AI-powered revenue management platform\nto cruise lines with 5+ ships operating in Caribbean and Mediterranean itineraries.” The more specific\nyour context, the more useful the output.\n2. Push Back on First Drafts\nThe first output is rarely the best. Challenge the AI: “This feels generic. Make it more specific to cruise\nline operations.” or “Your assumptions don’t match the Vertical Intelligence Brief. Here’s what I know—\nrevise accordingly.”\n3. Ask for Alternatives\nWhen you receive a recommendation, ask: “What are two alternative approaches? What are the trade-\noffs of each?” This builds critical thinking skills and ensures you make a deliberate choice.\n4. Request the Math\nFor any quantitative claim, ask: “Show me the math step-by-step.” This applies to TAM estimates,\npipeline models, ROI calculations, and capacity planning.\n5. Use the [DATA] / [ESTIMATE] / [ASSUMPTION] Labels\nThis discipline forces both you and the AI to distinguish between verified facts, informed projections,\nand unvalidated beliefs. It makes your plan more credible and auditable.\n6. Cross-Reference Constantly\nAfter every 2–3 sections, ask: “Review Sections 1 through [current] for internal contradictions. Are the\nICP, sales motion, pipeline math, and pricing all telling the same story?”\n7. Think Like a Skeptic\nBefore finalizing any section, ask: “If a skeptical CFO or board member reviewed this, what would they\nchallenge? Prepare me for those questions.”", "# | Phase | Section | Key Output\n1 | Strategy | Executive Overview | GTM thesis statement\n2 | Strategy | Market & Opportunity Analysis | TAM/SAM/SOM table with math\n3 | Strategy | Ideal Customer Profile (ICP) | Primary ICP reference card\n4 | Architecture | Buying Committee Architecture | Buying committee map (table)\n5 | Architecture | Value Quantification Model | Value driver table with calculations\n6 | Architecture | Pricing & Packaging Strategy | Pricing model recommendation\n7 | Architecture | Sales Motion Design | Sales motion type with justification\n8 | Architecture | Customer Journey & Sales Process | Buyer journey map\nMapping\n9 | Architecture | Revenue & Pipeline Model | Revenue waterfall model\n10 | Execution | Demand Generation & Acquisition | Channel strategy matrix\n11 | Execution | Sales Enablement | Pitch deck outline\n12 | Execution | AI-Enabled Sales Strategy | AI use case matrix (table)\n13 | Execution | KPIs & Dashboard Design | Leading indicator table\n14 | Execution | 90-Day Launch Plan | 30-day milestone plan\n15 | Defense | Risk & Mitigation | Risk matrix (12 risks, 4 categories)\n16 | Defense | Board Defense Preparation | 10 board-ready responses\n17 | Defense | Strategic Coherence Check | 8-dimension coherence matrix\nAppendix\nPage 49", "#\nPhase\nSection\nKey Output\n1\nStrategy\nExecutive Overview\nGTM thesis statement\n2\nStrategy\nMarket & Opportunity Analysis\nTAM/SAM/SOM table with math\n3\nStrategy\nIdeal Customer Profile (ICP)\nPrimary ICP reference card\n4\nArchitecture\nBuying Committee Architecture\nBuying committee map (table)\n5\nArchitecture\nValue Quantification Model\nValue driver table with calculations\n6\nArchitecture\nPricing & Packaging Strategy\nPricing model recommendation\n7\nArchitecture\nSales Motion Design\nSales motion type with justification\n8\nArchitecture\nCustomer Journey & Sales Process\nMapping\nBuyer journey map\n9\nArchitecture\nRevenue & Pipeline Model\nRevenue waterfall model\n10\nExecution\nDemand Generation & Acquisition\nChannel strategy matrix\n11\nExecution\nSales Enablement\nPitch deck outline\n12\nExecution\nAI-Enabled Sales Strategy\nAI use case matrix (table)\n13\nExecution\nKPIs & Dashboard Design\nLeading indicator table\n14\nExecution\n90-Day Launch Plan\n30-day milestone plan\n15\nDefense\nRisk & Mitigation\nRisk matrix (12 risks, 4 categories)\n16\nDefense\nBoard Defense Preparation\n10 board-ready responses\n17\nDefense\nStrategic Coherence Check\n8-dimension coherence matrix"]